2.11 - USB Connector Types: (Treat as simple)
Legacy serial vs USB

* Serial connectors: DB9 and DB25, with thumbscrews; DB9 is most common.

* Serial speed: up to 115 Kb/s, one device per serial port.

* USB can support up to 127 devices per controller via hubs and daisy chaining (theoretical max; real limits lower).

* All devices on one USB controller share the same total bandwidth.

USB version speeds (data rates)

* USB 1.0: 1.5 Mb/s (low speed).

* USB 1.1 (full speed): 12 Mb/s.

* USB 2.0 (high speed): 480 Mb/s.

* USB 3.0 / 3.1 Gen 1 (SuperSpeed): 5 Gb/s; look for “SS” marking.

* USB 3.1 Gen 2 (SuperSpeed+ / SS 10): 10 Gb/s.

* USB 3.1 Gen 2x2 (SuperSpeed 20): 20 Gb/s.

* USB 4.0: up to 40 Gb/s.

USB cable length limits

* USB 1.0: max about 3 meters (~9 feet).

* USB 1.1 and 2.0: max about 5 meters (~15 feet).

* USB 3.0 and later: back to about 3 meters (~9 feet).

* Longer “off‑spec” cables exist, but cause signal loss and lower real speed; long USB 3.x cables may not reach full 5 Gb/s.

USB power limits

* USB 1.0/1.1/2.0 standard port: 500 mA (0.5 A).

* USB 3.0 and above standard port: 900 mA (0.9 A) ≈ 4.5 W.

* Dedicated charging / power delivery (PD) port: up to 1500 mA (1.5 A) ≈ 7.5 W.

* Charging from a PC USB 2.0 port is much slower than from a wall charger or high‑power PD port.

Key concepts to recall for exam

* More devices in a USB hub chain = each gets a share of the total bandwidth, not the full port speed.

* Higher USB versions give faster speeds but shorter recommended maximum cable lengths.

