Direct Answers (clear & concise):
Legacy Serial vs USB

Serial (DB9 most common, also DB25): Thumbscrews, max ~115 Kb/s, one device per port.
USB advantage: Up to 127 devices per controller (via hubs/daisy-chaining – real limit lower). All devices on one controller share total bandwidth.

USB Version Speeds (data rates) – memorize this table:

USB 1.0: 1.5 Mb/s (Low Speed)
USB 1.1: 12 Mb/s (Full Speed)
USB 2.0: 480 Mb/s (High Speed)
USB 3.0 / 3.1 Gen 1 (SuperSpeed): 5 Gb/s – look for “SS” marking
USB 3.1 Gen 2 (SuperSpeed+ / SS 10): 10 Gb/s
USB 3.1 Gen 2x2 (SuperSpeed 20): 20 Gb/s
USB 4.0: up to 40 Gb/s

USB Cable Length Limits

USB 1.0: ~3 m (9 ft)
USB 1.1 & 2.0: ~5 m (15 ft)
USB 3.0 and newer: back to ~3 m (9 ft)
→ Longer “off-spec” cables exist but cause signal degradation and reduced real speed.

USB Power Limits

USB 1.x/2.0 standard port: 500 mA (0.5 A)
USB 3.x standard port: 900 mA (0.9 A) ≈ 4.5 W
Dedicated charging/PD ports: up to 1.5 A (7.5 W) or much higher with USB Power Delivery
→ Charging from a PC USB 2.0 port is noticeably slower than a wall charger or PD port.

Key Exam Concepts (your notes are already strong):

More devices on a hub chain = each device gets a share of the total bandwidth, not full port speed.
Higher USB version = faster speed but usually shorter max cable length.
USB carries both data and power – always match version, cable length, and power needs when troubleshooting.

Quick Semantic Tree (roots → trunk → leaves):

Root: Computers need a universal way to connect peripherals for data + power.
Trunk: Serial (slow, 1 device) → USB (fast, many devices, shared bandwidth).
Branches: Speed generations (1.x → 4.0), cable length limits, power delivery.
Leaves: Exam images of ports/hubs + real troubleshooting (slow device? wrong version? too many devices? cable too long?).

* USB is used for both data and power; always match device needs with port version, cable length, and power capability.
